The paper proposes a new approach for non-line-of-sight imaging and tracking, which involves capturing a sequence of transient measurements along a single optical path at long standoff distances. This approach has potential applications in robotic vision and autonomous driving, which suggests that the paper may belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) or robotics (cs.RO) sub-categories. The paper also involves the use of inverse methods based on Expectation-Maximization, which suggests that it may also belong to the information theory (cs.IT) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves experimental results with a prototype keyhole imaging system, which suggests that it may also belong to the graphics (cs.GR) or other (cs.OH) sub-categories.
